Now that we have the cash flow for all the years, we can solve for the terminal value using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Terminal value}&=\dfrac{\text{Cash flow for Year 5}\times (1+\text{Growth rate})}{\text{WACC}-\text{Growth rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Terminal value}&=\dfrac{\$4,200,487.46\times(1+0.035)}{(0.0925-0.035)}\\[15 pt]
&=\$75,608,774.28
\end{aligned}$$

The terminal value of this is $\$75,608,774.28$. The terminal value is the value of the company after the forecasted period.
